snippet.textDisplay: Relaxers permanently break really important bonds in the hair causing it to dry out and become too  porous to retain moisture,  hence perpetual dryness and breakage. This significantly lessens the chance of length retention. That's why for many years people thought black people couldn't grow long hair (Not including those naturals with long hair that shrinks and looks short). It also causes  damage to the scalp, this hinders growth because it damages the follicles. There's also a host of health related issues that it's been linked to.  I wish it was never invented. They look "pretty" though

snippet.textDisplay:
So I got my first relaxer at 14 yrs old. I’ll be 50 this year. Yes, there was an addiction to the creamy crack. Not to brag but my hair was gorgeous and thick all these years.

But ... March ‘19 I went to get my regular relaxer and it would NOT straighten. In fact it just waved (not napped) back up. Why? Hormonal changes aka Menopause. So I wash, deep condition and blow dry and flat iron or wear it curly for a couple of days (I look wretched in curls).

Not sure if it was my grade of hair or only having four stylists over that period of time or if it was a miracle from above, but my hair was never damaged or fell out. 🤷🏾‍♀️ The chemicals were good to me.

snippet.textDisplay:
Hair School Horror Story:

When I was a junior in hair school, MAYBE had like 75 hours in, my instructor comes in and says that one of our aesthetician students daughters wanted her naturally curly, but caucasian, hair relaxed. She asked me to do it, and my instructor, of course, encouraged me to do it because no one else could, we had no other juniors and all of our seniors were booked. So I was sort of forced into it. Mind you, I wasn't even into READING the permanent texture chapter of our textbook, let alone prepared to do one of the services. Especially one so TIME SENSITIVE! Anyway, here I am, panicking doing this relaxer on someone closer to my own age than I was to her mother, and my instructor comes in to check on me and says that I need to hurry it up because of XYZ reasons. This doesn't help my panic, and eventually, my instructor ends up helping me finish this girls hair because I've now spent about an hour and a half and I'm not even halfway through her head of hair because I'm stressed and her hair is as thick as a baseball when in a ponytail. We finish her hair, and almost NOTHING happened. I felt so bad because I had been combing and tugging and messing with this girl's hair all in the hopes that she would have the nice straight hair she had been hoping to have for months. Of course, this girl was upset, but in the same respect, she shouldn't have had such high hopes given I had just gotten to that school, and she knew I was a junior and a new student, and that I had no clue what I was doing. The only time I've ever had higher anxiety was doing my practical exam lol.
snippet.textOriginal:
Hair School Horror Story:

When I was a junior in hair school, MAYBE had like 75 hours in, my instructor comes in and says that one of our aesthetician students daughters wanted her naturally curly, but caucasian, hair relaxed.  She asked me to do it, and my instructor, of course, encouraged me to do it because no one else could, we had no other juniors and all of our seniors were booked.  So I was sort of forced into it. Mind you, I wasn't even into READING the permanent texture chapter of our textbook, let alone prepared to do one of the services.  Especially one so TIME SENSITIVE!  Anyway, here I am, panicking doing this relaxer on someone closer to my own age than I was to her mother, and my instructor comes in to check on me and says that I need to hurry it up because of XYZ reasons.  This doesn't help my panic, and eventually, my instructor ends up helping me finish this girls hair because I've now spent about an hour and a half and I'm not even halfway through her head of hair because I'm stressed and her hair is as thick as a baseball when in a ponytail.  We finish her hair, and almost NOTHING happened.  I felt so bad because I had been combing and tugging and messing with this girl's hair all in the hopes that she would have the nice straight hair she had been hoping to have for months.  Of course, this girl was upset, but in the same respect, she shouldn't have had such high hopes given I had just gotten to that school, and she knew I was a junior and a new student, and that I had no clue what I was doing.  The only time I've ever had higher anxiety was doing my practical exam lol.
